Core System Architecture

Layer 1 — Ambient Capture Layer

Purpose: convert real-world care activity into event objects.

Inputs
	•	bedside monitors
	•	infusion pumps
	•	vitals machines
	•	barcode medication administration
	•	voice capture
	•	patient call lights
	•	bed sensors
	•	hallway location tracking
	•	nurse mobile interactions
	•	EHR context
	•	lab feeds
	•	imaging reports

Output

Standardized event objects.

Example:

ClinicalEvent {
  type: "pain_assessment",
  timestamp: T,
  source: "voice_capture",
  nurse_id: N,
  patient_id: P,
  data: {
     pain_score: 6,
     location: "left hip",
     intervention: "repositioning"
  },
  confidence: 0.92
}


⸻

Layer 2 — Clinical Event Engine

Transforms raw signals into clinical documentation primitives.

Event Types
	•	assessment
	•	vital
	•	intervention
	•	medication
	•	patient response
	•	mobility event
	•	intake/output
	•	wound observation
	•	education delivered
	•	escalation
	•	refusal

Events are normalized to avoid duplication.

⸻

Layer 3 — Patient State Engine

Maintains a continuously updated patient state model.

PatientState {
  neuro
  respiratory
  cardiovascular
  pain
  mobility
  skin
  lines_drains
  intake_output
  psychosocial
}

Each state dimension is updated by incoming events.

⸻

Layer 4 — Nurse Verification Gate

All AI documentation proposals pass through a human approval layer.

Actions available:
	•	approve
	•	edit
	•	reject
	•	convert to narrative
	•	escalate
	•	defer

No autonomous signing.

⸻

Layer 5 — Documentation Composer

Transforms structured state into chart artifacts.

Outputs include:
	•	flowsheet entries
	•	nursing notes
	•	shift summaries
	•	handoff notes
	•	discharge education summaries
	•	escalation messages
	•	incident drafts

Example generated note:

Patient alert and oriented x4 this shift.
Pain ranged 4–6/10 in left hip, improved with repositioning and acetaminophen.
Ambulated once with assistance.
Skin intact with no new breakdown.
Vital signs stable.


⸻

Layer 6 — Risk Sentinel

Pattern detection across event stream.

Flags:
	•	sepsis risk
	•	fall risk escalation
	•	oxygenation decline
	•	pain unmanaged
	•	delirium indicators
	•	pressure injury risk
	•	medication timing issues

All alerts are evidence-backed and non-alarmist.

